Core Expertise
This skill covers world-class capabilities in:

Speech structure and narrative arc design
Opening hooks and audience capture techniques
Vocal variety (tone, pace, volume, pauses)
Body language and stage movement
Filler word reduction (um, uh, like, you know)
Audience engagement and interaction techniques
Slide design principles for presentations
Stage fright and performance anxiety management
Storytelling frameworks for business contexts
Q&A handling and impromptu speaking

Methodologies & Frameworks
Structure: Monroe's Motivated Sequence, Problem-Solution-Benefit, Three-act structure, TED talk formula
Delivery: Toastmasters evaluation criteria, Amy Cuddy power posing, Vocal warm-ups, Breathing exercises
Storytelling: Hero's Journey (condensed), STAR for business stories, The And/But/Therefore framework
Anxiety: Cognitive reframing, Systematic desensitization, Visualization, Pre-performance routines
Slides: PechaKucha (20 slides × 20 seconds), 10-20-30 rule (Kawasaki), Visual storytelling over bullet points
Practice: Record and review, Mirror practice, Gradual audience scaling (1 → 5 → 20 → 100+)

Reference Documentation
1. Speech Architecture
Comprehensive guide covering:
- Hook: Start with a story, statistic, question, or bold statement (never "Hi, I'm...")
- Problem: Make the audience feel the pain or curiosity
- Solution: Present your message/idea/argument
- Evidence: Data, stories, examples that prove your point
- Call to Action: What should they do/think/feel after your speech?
- Close: Callback to opening, memorable final line (not "and yeah, that's it")

2. Delivery Mastery
Complete technique library:
- Pace: Slow down — nervous speakers speed up, master speakers use pauses
- Volume: Vary it — whisper for emphasis, project for energy
- Pitch: Monotone is the enemy — let your voice be expressive
- Gestures: Open, purposeful, above the waist, matched to content
- Eye contact: Hold 3-5 seconds per person/section, don't scan

3. Anxiety Management
Technical reference with:
- The reframe: Anxiety and excitement are physiologically identical — channel it
- Pre-speech routine: Breathwork (box breathing), Power pose (2 min), Visualization (success imagery)
- The first 60 seconds: If you survive those, the rest gets easier — rehearse them the most
- Progressive exposure: Small group → meeting room → conference stage → large audience
- Backup plan: Know what to do if you lose your place (pause, breathe, reference notes — the audience is rooting for you)

Speaking Patterns
Pattern 1: The 5-Minute Lightning Talk
Maximum impact in minimum time:
- 0:00-0:30 — Hook (story, stat, or question)
- 0:30-1:30 — Context/Problem (why this matters)
- 1:30-3:30 — Core message (ONE idea, not three)
- 3:30-4:30 — Evidence (one killer example or data point)
- 4:30-5:00 — Close with call to action + callback to hook
- Rule: 1 idea per 5 minutes — never try to say everything

Pattern 2: Business Presentation (15-20 min)
Executive-friendly format:
- Start with the conclusion (executives are impatient — lead with the answer)
- Support with 3 pillars (data, story, logic)
- Use slides as visual aids, not teleprompters (6 words max per slide)
- Interact: Ask a question at the 5-minute mark to break passive listening
- End with clear next steps and owners
- Leave time for Q&A (30% of total time allocated)

Pattern 3: Storytelling for Engagement
Making any talk memorable:
- Open with "I remember the moment when..." — instant attention
- Create stakes: What was at risk? Why should they care?
- Use sensory details: What did you see, hear, feel?
- The turning point: What changed? What did you learn?
- Connect it back: "And that's exactly why [your main point] matters"
- Vulnerability wins — perfection is forgettable, authenticity is memorable

Best Practices
Content
- ONE core message per talk — if they remember one thing, what is it?
- Stories > statistics — but statistics IN stories = gold
- The audience doesn't care about YOU — they care about what you can do for THEM
- Cut ruthlessly — a tight 10-minute talk beats a rambling 30-minute one
- End on time or early — NEVER run over

Delivery
- Silence is your most powerful tool — pause after key points for impact
- The first 10 seconds determine if they listen — nail your opening
- Filler word fix: Record yourself, count fillers, replace each with a pause
- Don't hide behind the podium — move with purpose, claim the space
- Practice the talk 7+ times out loud before delivery

Improvement
- Record every talk and watch it (painful but essential)
- Join Toastmasters or equivalent speaking practice group
- Start with low-stakes opportunities (team meetings, internal demos)
- Get feedback from trusted people: "What landed? What didn't?"
- The only way to get better at speaking is to speak — volume matters

